                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.252/58: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-25T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 25, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>119. Minister for Foreign Affairs today handed me draft of note which he proposes
                    as his reply to note from me of like tenor. Translation follows:</p>
                <p>[Here follows the text of the note, which, except for minor changes in wording,
                    is the same as the Foreign Minister’s note of September 28, printed on <ref
                        target="#pg_927">page 927</ref>.]</p>
                <p>Unless I receive instructions to the contrary I will exchange notes in these
                    terms with the Minister for Foreign Affairs at 4 p.m., Monday 28th.</p>
                <p>The Department will notice that this note secures for the commerce of the United
                    States not only the French rates effective from May 22nd but also a general
                    guarantee of most-favored-nation treatment. Furthermore without committing our
                    Government in advance to any special provisions it leaves the door open for
                    early negotiations of a general commercial treaty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
